title: 10 Famous Budweiser Super Bowl Commercials
text:
Budweiser Super Bowl ads are iconic, so I decided to include some of them in a video, especially the ones I think are the most famous. Many of them didn‚Äôt make it into my selection and the decision wasn't easy for me. However, the hardest part was finding them in a decent quality in the first place. It's as if the responsible ones didn't even bother to keep these gems available. Congratulations to Anheuser Busch, the advertising agencies, and all the people who created these jewels. I hope you enjoy them.

These ads are included:

1. Budweiser, ‚ÄúLost Dog‚Äù from the 2015 Super Bowl with Don Jeanes, the famous Clydesdales and a cute puppy ‚Äì this is actually a follow up to ‚ÄúPuppy Love‚Äù from the 2014 Super Bowl which is the follow up to "Brotherhood" from the 2013 Super Bowl

2. Budweiser, ‚ÄúFrogs‚Äù from the 1995 Super Bowl ‚Äì this famous ad introduced ‚ÄúBud‚Äù, ‚ÄúWeis‚Äù, and ‚ÄúEr‚Äù

3. Budweiser, ‚ÄúCanned‚Äù from the 1999 Super Bowl ‚Äì this one featured the lizard resp. chameleon ‚ÄúLouie‚Äù and ‚ÄúFrankie‚Äù as well as ‚ÄúBud‚Äù, ‚ÄúWeis‚Äù, and ‚ÄúEr‚Äù  in a series of ads during the game with the title ‚ÄúMaster Plan‚Äù

4. Budweiser, ‚ÄúDonkey‚Äù res. "Born a Donkey" from the 2004 Super Bowl 

5. Budweiser, ‚ÄúAudition‚Äù from the 2005 Super Bowl ‚Äì this one is a sequel to the previous one with many other animals

6. Budweiser, ‚ÄúLashing‚Äù or ‚ÄúSlapped‚Äù from the 1999 Super Bowl ‚Äì with the lizard resp. chameleon ‚ÄúLouie‚Äù and ‚ÄúFrankie‚Äù as well as ‚ÄúBud‚Äù, ‚ÄúWeis‚Äù, and ‚ÄúEr‚Äù in a series of ads during the game with the title ‚ÄúMaster Plan‚Äù

7. Budweiser, ‚ÄúKing Crab‚Äù resp. ‚ÄúCrabs‚Äù from the 2007 Super Bowl

8. Budweiser, ‚ÄúDalmatian‚Äù from the the 2007 Super Bowl

9. Budweiser, ‚ÄúClydesdale Team‚Äù resp. ‚ÄúHank‚Äù, ‚ÄúRocky‚Äù or ‚ÄúTraining‚Äù from the 2008 Super Bowl with a Dalmatian as trainer

10. Budweiser, ‚ÄúRespect‚Äù, also called "Tribute", ‚Äú9/11‚Äù or "Ground Zero Clydesdales Bow" from the 2002 Super Bowl featuring the Clydesdales bowing their heads in the direction where once the World Trade Center stood ‚Äì this extremely touching commercial was shown to pay respect and was aired only once. In 2011 there has been another version with the One World Trade Center in it and in 2021 another updated version. I‚Äôm using the original version that was shown during the Big Game.

+

11. Budweiser, ‚ÄúWhassup‚Äù from 1999, a commercial that has written history and actually never aired during a Super Bowl ‚Äì it came out in December 1999 and became immediately a hit, but at the 2000 Super Bowl "Whassup Girlfriend" resp. "Whassup Game" from the the series was shown, followed by "Whassup Come Home" with a dog and aliens in 2001.

11.5 Budweiser, "What Are You Doing" from the 2001 Super Bowl ‚Äì this one is less well known than the previous one but was an actual Super Bowl commercial and has a lot of fans for a very good reason.

11.75 Budweiser, "Out of Towner" from the 2002 Super Bowl, a continuation of the "Jersey Guys" resp. "How ya doin" campaign.

11.99 Budweiser, "Here Comes The King" from 1979 Super Bowl


-----------------------------------------------------------


The votes are in and the current winner is: "Respect" (Tribute, 9/11) #10,  followed by "Lost Dog" (Puppy) #1

Results in detail, status February 2022 (votes and positive mentions counted):

1. Respect (Tribute, 9/11): 66 votes/mentions
2. Lost Dog (Puppy): 37 votes/mentions
3. Here Comes The King: 9 votes/mentions
4. Clydesdale Team (Hank, Rocky, Training): 6 votes/mentions
5. Frogs 1 (Bud, Weis, Er): 5 votes/mentions
6. Frogs 3 (Slapped): 5 votes/mentions
7. Whassup: 5 votes/mentions
8. Frogs 2 Canned: 4 votes/mentions
9. Donkey: 3 votes/mentions
10. Out of Towner (How ya doin): 3 votes/mentions
11. Audition: 0 votes/mentions
12. King Crab: 0 votes/mentions
13. Dalmatian: 0 votes/mentions
14. What Are You Doing: 0 votes/mentions

Thanks to everybody who watched the video, voted and commented on it, liked it and subscribed to my channel ‚Äì I appreciate that very much!

title: Budweiser | Wind / Super Bowl
text: Just 100 companies are responsible for 71% of global carbon emissions, and Budweiser is one of them. What can a giant corporation do to be part of the solution? Turns out, the answer is Blowin‚Äô in the Wind. Budweiser will now be brewed with 100% wind power from all of 12 breweries in the US. We announced this commitment in a poetic Super Bowl Spot, and during the weekend of the Big Game, we powered the host city of Atlanta with wind power. Even our billboards were powered by the wind. This Bud‚Äôs for tomorrow.

title: Super Bowl 50 - Budweiser: "Not Backing Down" (2016)
text:
From the brewery to the hands of the people, various footage gives us a behind-the-scenes glance at Budweiser and highlights people drinking (not sipping) it. Bands and athletes shower themselves in the beer to celebrate, and it's enjoyed on the dance floor as well as at the bar -- just not with fruit, which is why the man drinking it at the bar flicks the lemon slice off his glass. It's not a hobby, not small, not soft. The Budweiser Clydesdales are not ponies, the beer is not imported and it's not backing down. Budweiser says it's not for everyone, but this Bud's for you.

Enjoy!

Beer brewing in Budweis dates back to the 13th century. A few hundred years later, two breweries were founded in the city that made beer which they called "Budweiser," both being beers from the city of Budweis, which was then a part of the Kingdom of Bohemia. In 1876, the American brewer Anheuser-Busch began making a beer which it also called "Budweiser". This led in 1907 to the "Budweiser trademark dispute" between beer companies claiming trademark rights to the name "Budweiser".

The Budweiser Clydesdales are the beverage industry's most recognizable mascots, and you can meet these famous horses by visiting the Anheuser-Busch Brewery right here in Merrimack, New Hampshire.

These high stepping horses make hundreds of public appearances every year, in addition to appearing in television commercials and other Budweiser Beer advertising.

The hitch of Clydesdales here in New Hampshire are just one of several owned by Budweiser, which offers free tours of it's brewery located at 221 Daniel Webster Highway, just off Route 3 at Exit 10.

Visitors are welcome to visit the Clydesdales at their picturesque stables on the property. You can usually find 8-10 Clydesdales at their stables which are open to the public free of charge all year around.

title: 1984 Budweiser Light "Bring Out Your Best": Larry Santos Detroit
text:
In this clip, here are a series of Budweiser Light beer commercials that aired nationally. 

The connection to Detroit in these clips is the singing of Larry Santos who for a time was a host on the Detroit produced children's show "Hot Fudge." Santos is an accomplished singer-songwriter whose voice was heard often on Detroit TV during the 1980s. 

These commercials have the same "Bring Out Your Best" theme and highlight the following sports: Football, Relay, Baseball, Basketball, Luge, Downhill Skiing and Hockey.

title: Bud Light Backlash After Partnering With Transgender Influencer Dylan Mulvaney!!
text:
Bud Light and Anheuser Busch have been facing backlash over their recent partnership with Dylan Mulvaney, a social media influencer with a history of controversial and offensive behavior online. Many people have criticized Bud Light for working with Mulvaney despite his history, arguing that it sends a message that such behavior is acceptable or excusable. Some people have even called for a boycott of Bud Light products as a result of the partnership.

Bud Light has since issued a statement in response to the backlash, stating that they "do not condone derogatory language or behavior of any kind" and that "we understand the concerns raised about a recent influencer partnership and we apologize for any offense that it may have caused." Despite this apology, it remains to be seen how the public will respond and whether the controversy will have a lasting impact on Bud Light's reputation. We discuss the ongoing backlash!

title: Bud Light - Ladies Night (1993)
text:
Bud has a long history of Marketing the Rainbow, which goes back at least two decades, when they started a collaboration with GLAAD. Yet, their communications have not always been subtle, or supportive.

In this classic commercial from 1993, four men in drag play out their game of make believe - in "Ladies' Night". 

AdRespect: "The ad isn't meant to parody transgendered persons or gays, it plays on the Ms. Doubtfire/Tootsie joke of obvious men dressing as women out of need - it's older than television. The campaign has been so successful it has run for many years and has carried variations that included Don Rickles mistakenly picking up one of the women. One variation that was shot but never aired included a Los Angeles drag queen."

title: Don Lemon weighs in on Dylan Mulvaney Bud Light controversy | New York Post
text:
On Friday‚Äôs ‚ÄúCNN This Morning,‚Äù co-host Don Lemon dismissed the brewing controversy around Bud Light using transgender influencer Dylan Mulvaney to promote its beer as ‚Äúcrazy‚Äù and ‚Äúridiculous.‚Äù 

‚ÄúBacklash, boycotts, support for beer company Bud Light after they launched a new ad campaign featuring transgender activist and influencer Dylan Mulvaney,‚Äù Lemon explained.

After playing a social media video of Mulvaney touting Bud Light cans with the influencer‚Äôs face on them, Lemon derided critics: ‚ÄúSo the buzzword ‚Äòwoke‚Äô was once again brought into the mix, with people posting videos of them dumping out beer, calling for a boycott.‚Äù 

However, he noted, ‚ÄúDespite all of this, an expert tells CNN that once the social media backlash blows over, the long-term benefits of the company taking a cultural stand like this may be more impactful.‚Äù

Turning to CNN business and politics correspondent Vanessa Yurkevich, Lemon remarked, ‚ÄúLook, I think it‚Äôs crazy, but I want you to walk this ‚Äî walk us through this.‚Äù 

Read more at https://nypost.com/2023/04/14/don-lem...

title: Why Budweiser Is No Longer The King Of Beer
text:
Anheuser-Busch InBev is the world's largest brewer with 500 brands in more than 100 countries. In 2016, Flemish Interbrew and Brazilian Ambev, together known as InBev, merged with the American legacy company Anheuser-Busch, which ultimately brought AB under the leadership of 3G Capital. 3G Capital is a Brazilian-American global investment firm whose tactics include an aggressive, and at times controversial, cost-cutting strategy. AB InBev's longtime priority of aggressive acquisitions has been coupled with a focus on profit and price per barrel rather than volume share. Premiumization and expanding beyond beer continue to be winning strategies. In 2021, the company amassed $54.3 billion in revenue with 169,000 employees worldwide. As overall beer consumption has declined, AB InBev has transformed from merely a beer company to the largest beverage company in the world.

title: 1994 Budweiser Light "Ladies Night" athletes in drag TV ad
text:
Guys in drag take advantage of "Ladies Night" specials to win at pool in this 1994 television commercial for Bud Light. The BetaGems channel also has "1984 Karla DeVito sings for Budweiser commercial," "Budweiser Blues 1987 musical TV commercial," "Hip-hop farmers 1993 Budweiser TV ad," and "Bud Light 1986 TV ad Todd Susman & Kevin Farley."

BetaGems are culled from an archive of over 1000 beta video tapes recorded from the early 1980s into the 1990s. Most feature live music performances broadcast on television in San Diego CA, though there are also rarely seen commercials, comedy clips, and other material that doesn't seem to be anywhere else on Youtube or online. 

Most of the tapes were recorded on a Sony SL-HFT7 Super Beta Theater Hi-Fi Stereo - the same model was refurbished and is being used for these digital transfers and uploads. In rare occasions where a BetaGems clip does appear elsewhere, we're only uploading if our own beta master is better quality or contains material not seen previously. Much footage comes from public television and public access broadcasts that the taper, who worked for a local cable TV production company in the 1980s, monitored nightly for several years. Some of the programming is strictly regional, mostly from the San Diego area.

The ordinance, R-19-2023, discusses ‚Äúpossible action regarding a Resolution adopting a procedure regarding ordinance
proposals initiated by individual members of the City Council.‚Äù Essentially, the ordinance requires a fiscal or city manager to review a proposal before it goes to council.
Seaman told reporters that changing the current procedure for establishing an ordinance gives City Manager Jorge Cervantes the ability to recommend ‚Äì or not recommend ‚Äì ordinances to the council.

title: Senate panel passes bill to ban transgender girls from girls sports in NC
text:
North Carolina took its first step to join more than 20 other states in banning transgender girls from playing on girls' sports teams in middle school and high school Tuesday morning.

If enacted into law, transgender girls would be prohibited from participating in sports that correspond with their gender identity under a bill that advanced Tuesday in the North Carolina Senate.

The Senate education committee advanced the "Fairness in Women's Sports Act" on a voice vote with Republicans on the panel saying such a blanket ban is necessary to protect biological girls and saying that the small number of transgender girls, estimated at 15, currently participating in North Carolina is too many.

title: Brantley Gilbert destroys Bud Light can over Dylan Mulvaney brew-haha | New York Post
text:
Country-music star Brantley Gilbert is the latest artist to take aim at Bud Light for its partnership with transgender TikTok star Dylan Mulvaney ‚Äî smashing a can of the beer at his weekend concert in Alabama.

The multiplatinum singer, who has given up drinking, was tossed a can of Bud Light while performing at Indian Mountain ATV Park in Piedmont, prompting him to shout, ‚ÄúF‚Äìk that!‚Äù

He smashed the can on the floor of the stage before a concertgoer tossed him a different brand of beer, which garnered an approving nod from the singer.

While his band riffed Queen‚Äôs ‚ÄúAnother One Bites the Dust,‚Äù Gilbert then tossed the beverage to one of his bandmates, who punched a hole in the can and shot-gunned the beer.

text:

https://www.thepublica.com/dylan-mulv...

Anheuser-Busch, the parent company of Bud Light, has suffered a loss of more than $5 billion since it announced its partnership with Dylan Mulvaney, a controversial transgender social media influencer.

Mulvaney ‚Äî a trans-identified male ‚Äî was featured on a limited release Bud Light can. Mulvaney promoted the brand in a series of social media posts and videos. One especially viral video featured Mulvaney sitting in a bubble bath, surrounded by Bud Light cans.

Since the announcement on March 31, Anheuser-Busch‚Äôs shares have fallen by nearly 4%, with the company‚Äôs market capitalization dropping from $132.38 billion to $127.13 billion on Wednesday. The company‚Äôs shares fell by more than 1.5% on Wednesday alone.

title: Budweiser Beer Commercial!  Audio by SpotWorks Production
text:
Yes, we are a radio production company at http://www.radiocreative.com.  But often, clients come to us with a finished TV spot, but no audio.  Which was the case with this Budweiser commercial.  So I mixed the voice, sound effects and music for the TV spot.

On this spot I used the voice over services of Ken Eaken as featured at http://www.voiceoverselect.com.  From there, I mixed in the music and the sound effects to match the audio.

This spot was originally voiced by George Clooney, but Budweiser did not have the rights to use George in Paraguay (or did not want to pay to use him there). Perhaps they thought, why spend the money when people may not even recognize his voice.  So they had us provide the voice and produce the audio for that market.

*This transcript was generated by a third-party transcription software company, so please excuse any typos.

A nonprofit conservative group called Consumers Research has launched a new app that will let shoppers know which products they want to buy are woke, so that of course they can avoid those products. To put it another way, a conservative group has put together this app so that other conservatives don't have to worry about any products that might hurt their little feelings because there's such snowflakes that, God forbid you buy a product from a company that doesn't 100% share your values. That's how terrified Republicans are of buying these so-called woke products. Even though not a single person there on the right can tell you what woke actually means. Now here's the thing. These corporations that Republicans are going after, you know it, it doesn't matter if it's Anheuser-Busch, it doesn't matter if it's, you know, the coolers, the coffee makers, uh uh, the shoes, the other beverages, the books. 

A lot of the parent companies of these products share the same values as Republicans. Like we don't think people should have time off work. We think we should be able to pay them lower than minimum wage. We don't want to have have to offer benefits to them while they work for us. We don't wanna have to do anything to keep them safe. We wanna be able to pay them below minimum wage. That's what a lot of these companies that Republicans are now boycotting stand for, which is pretty much what the Republican Party stands for. The only area where there's a slight bit of difference, and most of that difference really is just for the cameras, is on social issues. That's it. But social issues are the only thing that matters to Republicans these days. It's a losing issue for them. They're not doing well with it. They're going to get trounced in 2024 because of it, but here they are with a new app that will let them take it and run with it. 

Do what you gotta do, guys. Listen, vote with your dollars. I get it. But think about this for a second. Republicans are out there boycotting, you know, whether it's books or coolers or coffee makers or beers, because those products at one point said, Hey, you know what? Let's kind of be inclusive a little bit. That's it. Now, when, when people on the left, when the progressives go out there and boy, uh, boycott a company, it's because, hey, this company just dumped these cancer causing toxins into the river and a hundred thousand people are gonna die in the next 20 years. Or, Hey, this company is so bad, they're making people pee in jars and not letting them get a break so they can go to the bathroom. It's a crap company. Let's not shop there. 

So do you see the difference between the boycotts on the left and the right? The right is like, oh my God, a transgender person is drinking Bud Light. Now I have to hate them, versus liberals or leftists who say, you know what? It's probably not a good idea to shop at a company that's making people pee and bottles because they're mistreating them so badly. But even then, we don't have to have a little app on our phone to tell us, oh no, you're touching a bad product. You know why? Because we're not the ones who are the delicate little snowflakes. That distinction rest with conservatives alone.

Multiple YouTubers are feeling the pinch when it comes to covering this topic. Tim Poll had two videos taken down, The Quartering had another removed, and Matt Walsh lost demonetization from his channel. If this is what is happening to moderate creators, the censorship scythe is coming for us all ahead of the most inclusive and diverse Pride Month ever.
